Project:
- program name: lxe
- purpose: Limited two-pass SIC/XE assembler.
- inputs: one or more assembler source files passed via command line.
- outputs per input
  - <name>.l listing file
  - <name>.st symbol table file


Class and assignment information:
- Class: CS530
- Assignment: Project 2, a limited XE assembler


File manifest:
- main.cpp
- assembler_types.h
- parser.h, parser.cpp
- optab.h, optab.cpp
- symtab.h, symtab.cpp
- pass1.h, pass1.cpp
- pass2.h, pass2.cpp
- listing.h, listing.cpp
- Makefile
- README
- sample/p1.sic
- sample2/p2.sic
- sample3/p3.sic


Compiling instructions:
1) Run: make
2) Executable created: ./lxe


Usage instructions:
1) Run: ./lxe ./sample/p1.sic [file2.sic ...]
2) If no arguments are provided, lxe prints a message and exits.


Design Decisions:
Draft:
- Two-pass pipeline:
  - Pass 1 computes addresses and builds symbol table.
  - Pass 2 resolves symbols and emits object code for listing lines.
- optab is a static in-memory table for SIC/XE opcodes and valid formats
- parser supports label/opcode/operand/comment fields and addressing markers
  (+, `#`, @, ,X) in source text.

Final Design Decisions:
The first decisions were regarding what language and compiler we should use, and we quickly came to the same conclusion,
C++ and GCC as the compiler. We were both more familiar with C++ than C and that was the case for the GCC compiler as well.
The language and compiler both suited to our strengths and was a straightforward decision.

Another decision was how to organize the overall design of the code base and we choose a modular object-oriented approach
using classes and structs where applicable. This decision was once more based on our experience in using this modular
approach of dividing code across classes and interweaving their functionalities. The readability and logic flow is also far
better than one monolithic file.

Thereafter, we decided that we first need to create a parser class to extract tokens from the source SIC/XE code.
We chose to delimit tokens such as labels using whitespace.Then, we created 3 structs in assembler_types.h to group together
data pertaining to each source line, op entry, and listing record. We decided that structs were better fit for this,
as opposed to creating 3 more new classes just for them to hold a few fields, as the structs didn’t even have functions.
In the OpEntry struct, we decided to use a bitmask int for valid instruction formats. The bitmask elegantly and efficiently
encodes the instruction format and validating the format is as simple as a quick bitwise operation.

The next design decision was how to create the table of ops and correspond them to their mnemonics and values.
This time we used a class because there were a few methods that we were going to need such as checking if the OpTable
already has an op, what the value of a mnemonic is, and more. Then came the organization of the ops, the most straightforward
approach was to use an unordered map to store an OpEntry struct from assembler_types as the value and the op mnemonic as the key.
This nicely organized the data without the need for any extra complexity and its O(1) amortized time complexity.

Subsequently, we needed to decide on a way to store the symbol table. Similar to the OpTable, we felt a class was best suited
for the task as we would need to look up the symbol table for the passes. We could have used a simple array, however,
we wanted to search for the values using symbols and the best choice was to once again use a map. We used the symbols as
keys and their address values as the values. Additionally, this prevents the chance that you might have duplicate symbols
in the table. It also simplifies searches and inserts.

Next, we chose to use classes for both pass 1 and pass 2. For pass 1, we used a struct to store the results of pass 1 instead
of simply using the fields of the pass 1 class to store these values. This was a better approach because this keeps pass 1
stateless and reusable across multiple SIC source files. The same approach was used in pass 2 and its class. Afterward,
we needed to decide on the type of addressing mode by default. We choose to resolve displacement first by pc-relative
addressing, then base-relative addressing. This was the proper approach the SIC/XE algorithm uses. In pass 2, we once more
determined using an int with bitshifting was the best approach for capturing the flag values for x, b, p, e. Comparisons are
simple and fast this way.

The approach to error handling was to catalog all errors into an error list and to display these to the user so that they are
aware of all the errors. We applied this approach to every possible point of failure.

Lastly, we created a simple ListingWriter class with two methods to output to the listing file and symbol table file.
We felt this was a better approach as it decoupled the logic, as opposed to adding these two functions onto another class.


Extra features:
- Multi-file invocation in one run. You can pass multiple files to the assembler and it will process them all.
- Basic error reporting for duplicate symbols, unknown opcodes, and range failures. The map data structure, which uses symbols as keys, prevents duplicate symbols from being added to the symbol table. 
- Collection and display of errors in a list format. This is a simple and effective way to display all errors to the user, not just the first error.
- Catching unknown or unsupported directives and opcodes. This is done by checking if the opcode is supported by the optab and if not, adding an error to the error list.
- Automatic output filename generation. The assembler will automatically generate the listing and symbol table files with the same name as the source file, but with the .l and .st extensions respectively.


Known bugs / things to improve:
- This initial version does not implement directives outside assignment scope
  (EQU/ORG/LTORG/EXTDEF/EXTREF/CSECT)


Lessons Learned:
- We learned the power of separating data from behavior as in the case of Pass1Result and Pass2Result.
- We learned how properly utilize a Software Design Document to plan and organize the code base. To have a clear and concise plan before starting to code.